# Controller Patterns

Controllers handle HTTP request/response and delegate to services.

## Structure

```typescript
import { Request, Response } from "express";
import { validationResult } from "express-validator";

class FeatureController {
  async methodName(req: Request, res: Response): Promise<void> {
    // Implementation
  }
}

export default new FeatureController();
```

## Response Format

All responses MUST use consistent structure:

```typescript
// ✅ Success Response
res.status(200).json({
  success: true,
  data: result,
  message?: "Optional message"
});

// ✅ Error Response
res.status(400).json({
  success: false,
  error: "ERROR_CODE",
  message: "Error description"
});
```

## Validation Handling

```typescript
// ✅ Check validation results first
const errors = validationResult(req);
if (!errors.isEmpty()) {
  res.status(400).json({
    success: false,
    error: "BAD_REQUEST",
    message: errors.array()
  });
  return;
}
```

## Error Handling

```typescript
// ✅ Wrap in try-catch
try {
  const result = await service.doSomething();
  res.status(200).json({ success: true, data: result });
} catch (error) {
  res.status(500).json({
    success: false,
    error: "Failed to perform action",
    message: error instanceof Error ? error.message : "Unknown error"
  });
}
```

## Query Parameters

```typescript
// ✅ Validate query parameters
const { id } = req.query;
if (!id || typeof id !== "string") {
  res.status(400).json({
    success: false,
    error: "BAD_REQUEST",
    message: "ID query parameter is required"
  });
  return;
}
```

## Rules

- Always return `Promise<void>`
- Never throw errors - always respond with JSON
- Check for null/undefined from service layer
- Use appropriate HTTP status codes (200, 201, 400, 404, 409, 500)
